{
  "local_port": 54670,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are traditional British dishes?",
  "response": "Traditional British dishes are a reflection of the country\u2019s history, culture, and regional diversity. Here are some classic British dishes that are well-known and cherished:\n\n### 1. **Fish and Chips**\n   - A quintessential British dish featuring battered and fried fish (usually cod or haddock) served with thick-cut chips (fries). Often accompanied by mushy peas, tartar sauce, and a sprinkle of salt and vinegar.\n\n### 2. **Full English Breakfast**\n   - A hearty morning meal typically including eggs (fried or scrambled), bacon, sausages, baked beans, grilled tomatoes, mushrooms, black pudding, and toast or fried bread.\n\n### 3. **Sunday Roast**\n   - A traditional meal served on Sundays, consisting of roasted meat (beef, lamb, chicken, or pork), roast potatoes, Yorkshire pudding, vegetables (like carrots, parsnips, and Brussels sprouts), and gravy.\n\n### 4. **Shepherd\u2019s Pie**\n   - A comforting dish made with minced lamb (or beef, in which case it\u2019s called Cottage Pie), topped with a layer of mashed potatoes and baked until golden.\n\n### 5. **Bangers and Mash**\n   - A simple yet beloved dish of sausages (\"bangers\") served with mashed potatoes and onion gravy.\n\n### 6. **Beef Wellington**\n   - A luxurious dish of beef fillet coated with p\u00e2t\u00e9 and duxelles (a mixture of mushrooms, onions, and herbs), wrapped in puff pastry, and baked.\n\n### 7. **Cornish Pasty**\n   - A pastry filled with beef, potatoes, swede (rutabaga), and onions, originating from Cornwall. It was traditionally a portable meal for miners.\n\n### 8. **Ploughman's Lunch**\n   - A cold meal typically including cheese (like Cheddar), pickles, bread, and sometimes cold meats, boiled eggs, and salad.\n\n### 9. **Toad in the Hole**\n   - Sausages baked in a Yorkshire pudding batter, creating a puffy, savory dish similar to a giant popover.\n\n### 10. **Pie and Mash**\n   - A working-class dish featuring minced beef pies served with mashed potatoes and a parsley liquor (sauce).\n\n### 11. **Bakewell Tart**\n   - A sweet dessert from Bakewell, Derbyshire, made with a shortcrust pastry base, a layer of jam, and a frangipane (almond) filling, often topped with icing and a cherry.\n\n### 12. **Spotted Dick**\n   - A traditional steamed pudding made with suet, flour, and dried fruit (usually currants or raisins), often served with custard.\n\n### 13. **Eton Mess**\n   - A dessert made with crushed meringue, whipped cream, and strawberries, reflecting a whimsical, messy presentation.\n\n### 14. **Black Pudding**\n   - A type of blood sausage made with pork blood, fat, and oats, often served as part of a full English breakfast.\n\n### 15. **Haggis**\n   - While more closely associated with Scotland, haggis is also enjoyed in parts of England. It\u2019s a savory pudding made from sheep\u2019s offal (heart, liver, and lungs), oatmeal, and spices, traditionally cooked in a sheep\u2019s stomach.\n\n### 16. **Scotch Egg**\n   - A boiled egg wrapped in sausage meat, coated in breadcrumbs, and deep-fried or baked.\n\n### 17. **Lancashire Hotpot**\n   - A hearty stew made with lamb or beef, onions, and potatoes, slow-cooked in a lidded pot.\n\n### 18. **Eccles Cakes**\n   - Small, round pastries filled with currants and spices, named after the town of Eccles in Greater Manchester.\n\n### 19. **Welsh Rarebit**\n   - A savory dish of melted cheese (often Cheddar) mixed with ale or mustard, served on toasted bread.\n\n### 20. **Clotted Cream and Scones**\n   - A classic afternoon tea treat, featuring scones served with clotted cream and jam (often strawberry).\n\n### 21. **Jam Roly-Poly**\n   - A traditional pudding made with suet pastry spread with jam, rolled up, and steamed or baked, usually served with custard.\n\nThese dishes showcase the rich culinary heritage of the UK, with influences from its history, agriculture, and regional traditions.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
